They had moored their boat one night under a bank veiled in high grasses and short pollarded trees . 
Sleep , after heavy sculling , had come to them early , and by a corresponding accident they awoke before it was light . 
Both men had simultaneously a reminiscence of childhood , of the elfin and adventurous time when tall weeds close over us like woods . 
Standing up thus against the large low moon , the daisies really seemed to be giant daisies , the dandelions to be giant dandelions . 
Somehow it reminded them of the dado of a nursery wall paper . 
The drop of the river bed sufficed to sink them under the roots of all shrubs and flowers and make them gaze upwards at the grass . 
By Jove ! said Flambeau , it's like being in fairyland . 
Father Brown sat bolt upright in the boat and crossed himself . 
